 With regard to the 'Interstellar extinction and attenuation', the interstellar extinction is that if there are some materials such as dust grains or atmosphere, also known as 'interstellar medium', between the observer and the stars which release the electromagnatic wave and photons, these wave and photons are absorbed or scattered by those materials out of line-of-sight, which means that the measurement by the observers can be inclined. In this process, the more fine dust is at there, the clearer the extinction effect is. However, although the extinction is occered by the dust grains, but all the dust grains are not making the comparable effect. In short, the condition of the dust grains is essential requisite for different extinction and attenuation. For instance, the fine dust grains make the distinct extinction effect. Moreover, the blue light affects more influnce than the red light, so the stars which are located behide the dust cloud are seemed much redder, and this effect is known as 'Interstellar reddening'. This is because the blue light has shorter wavelength than the red one, so the blue light is more heavily reddened. This shows that the Interstellar reddening is inversely proportional with the wavelength of the light. The more extinction effects make the more reddening effects. Surely, the scattering the photons by the dust grains can provoke the phenomenon which the light goes into the line-of-sight because the distance between the column of the dust grains and the star are far from each other. However, the amount of this light is small, so this can be safely ignored. Both absorption and scattering out of line-of-sight are directly proportional with the amount of the dust grains. Furthermore, if there are equivalent column of dust grains and different wavelengthes, these wavelengthes does not vary. This means that the nomarlized extinction curves by different stars with the different amount of identical dust grains are comparable.\par
\par
(the relation of the extinction effect with the amount of the dust grains : \par
1. the more amount of dust grains makes the distinct extinction\par
2. the amount of dust grains is not affecting the amount of the extinction effect.)\par
\par
 1. The extinction effect\par
 The extinction effect, also known as interstellar extinction or just extinction, is occured when there are some materials such as dust grains and gas, called as interstellar medium(ISM), between the observer and the emitting stars which release the electromagnatic radiations as well as photons. It can arise by not only the dust grains and gas between the observer and stars(intersellar medium), but also the atmosphere around the observer and dust grains near around the stars which is known as circumstellar dust. Because the blue light is much more strongly attenuated than the red one, the extinction effect causes that the stars appeares redder than expected and inherented brightness, and this phenomenon is kwnons as 'Interstellar reddening'.\par
 If there are homogenous spherical dust particles, the introduce the cross section for extinction is\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f1\fs24\'f3\f0\lang1042 (\f1\'eb\f0 ) = \f2\u-10187?\u-8321?\f0 a\super 2\nosupersub Q\sub ext\nosupersub (\f1\'eb\f0 )\fs30\par
\fs20 (a : the radius of the dust,\par
\lang18 Q\sub ext\nosupersub (\f1\lang1042\'eb\f0 )\lang18  : efficiency factor of extinction)\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  The equation of the optical depth along the line-of-sight with the volumetric dust density n\sub d \nosupersub is then\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f1\fs24\'f4\sub\f0\lang1042 lambda\super ext \nosupersub = \'a1\'f2\b n\sub\b0 dust \nosupersub\f1\lang18\'f3\sub\f0\lang1042 lambda\super ext \nosupersub ds \par
