 3. Interstellar reddening\par
 As mentioned above the extinction effect, the interstellar reddening is occuered by the interstellar medium by extinguishing the background starlight. When it comes to the wavelength, the wavelength depends on the extinction and the short-wavelength is extinguished more than long-wavelenght. As a result, the short-wavelength causes the redder appearence. This phenomenon is called as 'Interstellar reddening'. To be more specific, the because the short-wavelength is strongly absorbed or scattered by dust grains than long-wavelength is that the dust grains have typical size which is comparable with the short-wavelength one. Therefore, the short-wavelength such as blue light is heavily absorbed and scattered before it reaches to observer by making the stars are appeared redder than they really are.\par
 The reddening of observing objects is inversely proportional with the wavelengths of the optical light. The degree of reddening can be calculated with following equation\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\fs24 E(B-V) = (B-V) - (B-V)\sub 0\par
\nosupersub\fs20 ( (B-V) : colour index of the object,\par
(B-V)\sub 0\nosupersub  : true colour index )\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  It is possible to expect that the more interstellar medium such as dust grains, the more pronounced the reddening and the higher the extinction effect. This is because the dust grains and the starlights are the extricable linked each other, which means that it is inevitable that the starlight aheading to the observer from distant star cannot help being constrained by the dust grains. The extinction and reddening equation is  :\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\fs24 A\sub v \nosupersub = 3.2E(B-V)\par
\fs20 (A\sub v \nosupersub : the extinction measured in the V band)\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  The distance equation is that : \par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\fs24 d = 10\super 0.2(m - M + 5 - A\sub v\super )\nosupersub  [pc]\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\fs20  In this equation, it is possible to compute the magnitude of the loss light by subtracting the extinction in the exponent of this equation.\par
\par
 4. Optical depth\par
 The optical depth of a material is denoted \f1\lang1042\'f4\f0  and given by\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f1\fs24\'f4\f0  = ln(\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super i\nosupersub  / \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super t\nosupersub ) = -lnT\fs20\par
\lang18 (\f1\'d6\sub\f0\lang1042 e\super i\nosupersub  : the radiant flux received by the material,\par
\f1\lang18\'d6\sub\f0\lang1042 e\super t\nosupersub  : the radiant flux transmitted by the material,\par
T : the transmittance of the material)\par
\par
\fs24 T\super -1\nosupersub  = \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super i\nosupersub  / \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super t\nosupersub\par
T = \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super t\nosupersub  / \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super i\par
\fs20\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  \nosupersub The spectral optical depth in frequency and in wavelength is that\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f1\fs24\'f4\sub\f0 v\nosupersub  = ln(\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e,v\super i\nosupersub  / \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e,v\super t\nosupersub ) = -lnT\sub v\nosupersub\par
\f1\'f4\sub\f0 lambda\nosupersub  = ln(\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e,lambda\super i\nosupersub  / \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e,lambda\super t\nosupersub ) = -lnT\sub lambda  \nosupersub\fs20 (lambda = \f1\'eb\f0 )\par
\par
(\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e,v\super i\nosupersub  : the spectral radiant flux in frequency received by the material,\par
\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e,v\super t\nosupersub  : the spectral radiant flux in frequency transmitted by the material,\par
