 5. The relationship between optical depth and attenuation\par
 The attenuation of transmitted radiant power in metarial can be measured by utilizing the optical depth. This can be caused by absorption, reflection, scattering, and other physical processes. The optical depth is approximately comparable with its attenuation when both the absorbance is less than 1 and the emittance of the material is also much less than optical depth.\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f1\fs24\lang1042\'d6\sub\f0 e\super t\nosupersub  + \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super a\nosupersub  = \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super i\nosupersub  + \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super e\nosupersub\par
T + A = 1 + E\par
\fs20 (\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super t\nosupersub  : the radiant power transmitted by the material,\par
\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super a\nosupersub  : the radiant power attenuated by the material,\par
\f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super i\nosupersub  : the radiant power received by th material,\par
\f1\'d6\f0\-\sub e\super e\nosupersub  : the radiant power emitted by the material)\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  The attenunace and emittance is\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\fs24 A = \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super a\nosupersub  / \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super i\nosupersub  \fs20 (attenuance of the material)\par
\fs24 E = \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super e\nosupersub  / \f1\'d6\sub\f0 e\super i\nosupersub  \fs20 (emittance of the material)\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  According to the optical depth equation of the material, the transmittance of the material can be denoted with \f1\fs24\'f4\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f0 T = e\super ^-\nosupersub\f1\'f4\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0  \fs20 This can be explained by Beer-Lamber law. Therefore, the attenuance of the material is\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\fs24 A = 1 - e^-\f1\'f4\f0  + E\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  \fs20 Approximately,\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f1\fs24\'f4\f0  + E -> \f1\'f4\f0  (\f1\'f4\f0  <<1 and E << \f1\'f4\f0 )\f1\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f0  \fs20 5-(1). Beer-Lambert Law\par
 The Beer-Lamber Law relates with the attenuation of the light when the light travels the material. This relates the material which contains the single attenuating species of uniform concentration to the optical path length through specimen and absorptivity. The common mathmetical formulation is \f1\fs24\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\f0 A = \f1\'e5\f0 lc\f1\par
\f0\fs20\lang18 (A : the absorbance,\par
\f1\'e5\f0\lang1042  : the molar attenuation coefficient or absorptivity of the attenuating species,\par
l : the optical path length,\par
c : the concentration of the attenuating species)\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1  Above equation is also defined with N which is the number of the different medium the light is travelling and with T which is the transmittance like that\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\fs24 T = e^-(\f1\'d3\sub\f0 i=1\super N\nosupersub  \f1\'f3\sub\f0 i\nosupersub  \'a1\'f2\sub 0\super l\nosupersub  n\sub i\nosupersub (z)dz) = 10^-(\f1\'d3\sub\f0 i=1\super N \nosupersub\f1\'e5\sub\f0 i\nosupersub  \'a1\'f2\sub 0\super l\nosupersub  c\sub i\nosupersub (z)dz)\par
\fs20\par

\pard\sa200\sl240\slmult1\lang18  Or equivalent equations eliminating the integrals in the exponential part can be expressed with the optical depth \f1\lang1042\'f4\f0  and the absorbance A\par
\lang18\par

\pard\sa200\sl240\slmult1\qc\f1\fs24\lang1042\'f4\f0  = \f1\'d3\f0\-\sub i=1\super N\nosupersub  \f1\'f4\sub\f0 i\nosupersub  = \f1\'d3\sub\f0 i=1\super N\nosupersub  \f1\'f3\sub\f0 i\nosupersub  \'a1\'f2\sub 0\super l\nosupersub  n\sub i\nosupersub (z)dz\par
A = \f1\'d3\f0\-\sub i=1\super N\nosupersub  A\sub i\nosupersub  = \f1\'d3\f0\-\sub i=1\super N\nosupersub  \f1\'e5\sub\f0 i\nosupersub  \'a1\'f2\sub 0\super l\nosupersub  c\sub i\nosupersub (z)dz\par
\fs20\par
(\f1\'f3\sub\f0 i\nosupersub  : the attenuation cross section of the attenuating specimen i,\par
